{{imageframe|width=200|content= [[File:Diasymahiko mettalio nikis.jpg|70px]] [[File:Diasymmahiko mettalio nikis.jpg|65px]]|caption=Obverse and reverse of the medal}} The '''Inter-Allied Victory Medal''' ({{lang-el|Διασυμμαχικόν Μετάλλιον Νίκης}}) is a campaign medal issued by [[Greece]], commemorating the [[Allies of World War I|Allied]] victory in the [[World War I|First World War]]. The medal is the Greek version of a common design used among all Allied nations, following a proposal made by French Marshal [[Ferdinand Foch]], who was supreme commander of the Allied Forces during the war. Each medal, in bronze, has the same diameter (36&nbsp;mm) and ribbon (double rainbow), but with a national design representing a winged [[Victory]]. The Greek version of the medal was designed by [[Henry-Eugène Nocq]]. Approximately 200,000 medals were awarded.
